04339nam a22005175i 9780226148847DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20111994ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802261488477 a10.7208/97802261488472doi  a(DE-B1597)523584  a(OCoLC)1015882064  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQ175 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306.4/5/0941090321 aShapin, Steven, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Social History of Truth :bCivility and Science in Seventeenth-Century England /cSteven Shapin. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (512 p.) :b12 halftones, 2 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aScience and Its Conceptual Foundations series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Genres, Disciplines, and Conventions -- tThe Argument Summarized -- tCHAPTER ONE. The Great Civility: Trust, Truth, and Moral Order -- tCHAPTER TWO. "Who Was Then a Gentleman?" Integrity and Gentle Identity in Early Modern England -- tCHAPTER THREE. A Social History of Truth-Telling: Knowledge, Social Practice, and the Credibility of Gentlemen -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Who Was Robert Boyle? The Creation and Presentation of an Experimental Identity -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Epistemological Decorum: The Practical Management of Factual Testimony -- tCHAPTER SIX. Knowing about People and Knowing about Things: A Moral History of Scientific Credibility -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Certainty and Civility: Mathematics and Boyle's Experimental Conversation -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Invisible Technicians: Masters, Servants, and the Making of Experimental Knowledge -- tEpilogue: The Way We Live Now -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do we come to trust our knowledge of the world? What are the means by which we distinguish true from false accounts? Why do we credit one observational statement over another? In A Social History of Truth, Shapin engages these universal questions through an elegant recreation of a crucial period in the history of early modern science: the social world of gentlemen-philosophers in seventeenth-century England. Steven Shapin paints a vivid picture of the relations between gentlemanly culture and scientific practice. He argues that problems of credibility in science were practically solved through the codes and conventions of genteel conduct: trust, civility, honor, and integrity. These codes formed, and arguably still form, an important basis for securing reliable knowledge about the natural world. Shapin uses detailed historical narrative to argue about the establishment of factual knowledge both in science and in everyday practice. Accounts of the mores and manners of gentlemen-philosophers are used to illustrate Shapin's broad claim that trust is imperative for constituting every kind of knowledge. Knowledge-making is always a collective enterprise: people have to know whom to trust in order to know something about the natural world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aSciencexMoral and ethical aspectszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aSciencexSocial aspectszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226148847423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226148847.jpg  a978-3-11-066785-1  UChP eBook-Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles